snippet.textDisplay:
As a package combo of the hi vs. low challenge the tests you performed were effective, but to properly test the difference of individual upgraded modifications.
IMO...not enough data was captured to provide evidence that supports the hi=More Better claim for the tyres or wheels. I would have also tested (or shown the results for) the following tasks/trials:
▪tyre rolling resistance, which determines how freely the tyre rolls while maintaining grip. The result would show the lower the resistance will require less effort and load on the engine meaning better gas mileage = $$$ saved!!
▪the results of balancing the wheels and tyres as in my experience as a qualified mechanic shows that the quality, materials and workmanship that goes into reputable brand wheels and tyres makes a huge difference in the balancing as well as higher structural integrity and extended tyre life. Results would show less weight means better quality and workmanship. This again = $$$ same!!
▪to gather a definitive conclusion for the slide out test and the 60-0 stop test, each combination should be trialled on both cars. The results would show (and prove) how critical it is to have a suspension package designed and setup properly. I also believe the Federal's would give the same results as the Bridgestone's on the hi car as it did on the low car.

Thanks for putting the time and effort as well as spending the money to make this project happen. I think you will help allot of people make the right decisions when they upgrade they're own cars by making a purchase based on the evidence that performance and safety greatly outweighs saving a couple of bucks.

snippet.textDisplay: Wheel weight and total rotational weight makes a significant difference in acceleration, not nearly as much for braking or cornering. 4 pounds difference per wheel can actually change your 0-60mph acceleration times by a tenth of a second or more. 4 pound rotational weight saving affects your car about the same as reducing the car's overall weight by 15 pounds, so if all 4 tires are 4 pounds lighter each, your 0-60 time will be affected about the same as reducing your car's overall weight by 60 pounds.

snippet.textDisplay: So while I appreciate the effort I have some issues with the methodology.  The tires aren't the same at the same time the wheels aren't the same.  The cars aren't the same, is the ride height the same? Brakes, suspension? Too many variables at once guys, you want to test one change at a time.  I'm guessing this also isn't daily driver spec because these are extreme summer tires.  There is some data here but I wouldn't call it useful enough to actually draw conclusions from and it won't help inform people's purchases beyond some vague feelings rather than data from A:B testing.
